AB  - Part 3 of a 3-part series on the origins, impacts, and opponents of predatory journals. In 2014, the Ottawa Citizen newspaper successfully placed a “garbled blend of fake cardiology, Latin grammar, and missing graphs” into a oncereputable Canadian medical journal that had been sold to offshore owners. The journal, now possibly based in Turks and Caicos, accepted a payment of $1200 and published what the newspaper described as a deliberately bad, plagiarized study that substituted the word “cardiac” for “HIV.” The episode, if startling, is hardly isolated. Most members of the small academic subspecialty devoted to studying and tracking questionable publication practices agree that the problem is getting worse. If some shady journals are glaringly obvious, others are more carefully camou- flaged and creeping into scholarly indices and curriculum vitae alike. Efforts to curb the growing influence of these “predatory” publications, particularly in Asia, have been complicated by bitter debates between open access advocates and detractors over perceived biases, unsupported opinions, and unreliable data. Until recently, few efforts had matched the scope of Beall's List of Predatory Open-Access Publishers, a controversial but widely cited set of blacklists that flags dubious publishers, journals, and related companies. “The only thing I know to do is what I'm doing, which is helping people become aware of these publishers and journals so that they can avoid them,” says list curator Jeffrey Beall, associate professor and scholarly communications librarian at the University of Colorado in Denver. Other efforts are gaining momentum, however. The Directory of Open Access Journals (DOAJ), for example, has compiled a whitelist of high-quality and properly peer-reviewed publications. Two years ago, the DOAJ overhauled its application process and required every journal and publisher in its directory to reapply. Lars Bjørnshauge, the directory's managing director, who is based in Copenhagen, Denmark, says the reappraisal came in response to requests for more vetting from funders, universities, and other stakeholders. The application's new questions, Mr. Bjørnshauge says, dig deeply into the quality and transparency of each journal's editorial process. The reviewers also conduct spot checks on listed editorial board members to verify their willing participation, especially if, as he puts it, “we smell a dodgy publication.” Keeping up with the volume of “questionable” publishers and journals has been a challenge (Mr. Bjørnshauge dislikes the term “predatory”). However, the endeavor has been aided by 7 staff members and 50 volunteer associate editors from around the world. Funding has come from academic and open access publishing members in nearly 30 countries, as well as 33 sponsors that include most major scholarly publishers (Wiley, which publishes Cancer Cytopathology, is among them). Once the vetting process is complete, Mr. Bjørnshauge estimates that perhaps 8500 journals will be listed in the DOAJ, with another 8000 to 9000 journals having been either rejected or dropped due to noncompliance. “It's timeconsuming; it's labor-intensive,” says collaborator Heather Joseph, executive director of the Scholarly Publishing and Academic Resources Coalition (SPARC) in Washington, DC. “But it has to happen in order for the integrity of the open access publishing process and movement, frankly, to not be further tarnished by some of the bad players.” The DOAJ has also helped launch 2 related projects. One, funded by a grant from Canada's International Development Research Centre, is designed to help open-access journals in the Southern hemisphere improve their quality and is recruiting a team of regional ambassadors to be go-to educators. A related initiative called “Think. Check. Submit.” aims to help researchers discriminate between trustworthy and suspect journals via a checklist of quality indicators. Mr. Beall welcomes the competition, although he cautions that it is too early to say whether the latter campaign will succeed. “If somebody can find a better way to help people avoid predatory publishers and what I'm doing in a complementary way, that's great,” he says. Cabell's International, an academic publishing service in Beaumont, Texas, that curates its own journal directory, is using Mr. Beall's list, the DOAJ, and more than 3 dozen other selection criteria as part of a new initiative to reevaluate the journals included in its database. Despite the usefulness of such lists, other observers say, broader efforts may be needed to counter the advance of predatory publications. “I'm not aware of a single conference that has taken place to bring these disparate groups together to try to sort out a path forward,” says David Moher, PhD, senior scientist at the Ottawa Hospital Research Institute in Canada. The journalologist recently called for community-wide intervention in a recent editorial.1 If different factions can put aside their grievances, Dr. Moher says, a joint conference might help to highlight knowledge gaps, establish common standards, and establish research and intervention priorities. But who should play the leading role in bringing everyone together? Dr. Moher believes publishers enjoy a “very privileged position” within the industry and are the most logical choice to lead the way in organizing conferences and backing new initiatives such as a global fund to help defray author processing charges. Academic institutions, he says, also must play a more active role in protecting their researchers from shady publishing practices. The reason why we have such a vast predatory journal problem is that there is a market opportunity; that there are hundreds of thousands, if not millions, of researchers looking for a place to publish their work. —Jocalyn Clark, PhD Multiple universities in fact have begun sounding the alarm. The United Kingdom's University of Manchester, for example, has reviewed the common practices of questionable publications and warned its faculty not to use such journals. Savitribai Phule Pune University in India has issued its own guidelines and called out predatory journals and publishers by name. The stepped-up efforts also may spur more reappraisals of an academic reward system that critics say has long pressured researchers to publish in the “right” journals, and has created plenty of opportunities for abuse. “The reason why we have such a vast predatory journal problem is that there is a market opportunity; that there are hundreds of thousands, if not millions, of researchers looking for a place to publish their work,” says Jocalyn Clark, PhD, executive editor of The Lancet. Many are looking to do so using the path of least resistance, with few controls established by those mandated to oversee the research enterprise, she says. From that point of view, Dr. Clark says, it is hard to blame authors for publishing in scam journals if they are not being dissuaded or punished for doing so. “These predatory publishers are just seizing an opportunity,” she says. “That sort of indicts our research culture, which is so very, very focused on ‘publish or perish,’ ” she says. However, the geographical variation in predatory practices suggests that certain practices may exert more positive or negative pressure, says Ms. Joseph. “That gives me hope that a large portion of the spike and a big part of the problem can really be dealt with by asking research institutions to take a look internally at the incentive structures that they've got in place,” she says. Ms. Joseph, Mr. Bjørnshauge, and others say it may be equally instructive to dig into the publishing culture of Latin America, a region in which predatory practices have been much less pervasive to date. “Publish or perish is everywhere–it's in Latin America too,” says Renan Moritz Almeida, PhD, professor of biomedical engineering at the Federal University of Rio de Janeiro in Brazil, who also studies scientific integrity. The difference, he says, is that when researchers cannot land a study in a top-tier international journal, their second or even third option is normally not a predatory one. Instead, he says, a robust collection of second-tier journals has given local researchers a readily accessible outlet. In fact, Brazil is second only to the United States in the number of journals in the DOAJ (it gave up its top spot after the recent reapplication process). The majority of Latin America's journals are indexed in the Scientific Electronic Library Online (SciELO), a kind of PubMed for local and regional openaccess publications (mainly in Central and South America) in which English is not a priority. Many of those publications also are collaboratively funded by universities and funding agencies. Mr. Beall has questioned SciELO's quality, but Dr. Almeida says the publishing framework could be an example for other regions. “In my view, it's a successful system,” he says. Although the combined efforts have spurred cautious optimism in some quarters, Dr. Moher says significantly more resources will be required to understand, and undermine, the motives and mechanisms of predatory publishers. “That doesn't mean we're going to get rid of them all,” he says, “but we may be able to make inroads substantively.”
